WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:00.171
Right.

00:00.552 --> 00:03.115
So what does this thing do?

00:03.355 --> 00:09.062
It is a planning algorithm and planning might be not really familiar for you.

00:09.502 --> 00:20.976
So let's say you are in this room and or this set of rooms right here, there's a bunch of walls and you are up here and you want to reach the goal down here.

00:20.956 --> 00:30.977
So first of all, this is a goal directed problem, right here, it says goal directed goal directed means that you give the algorithm a goal to reach.

00:31.498 --> 00:36.028
And this could be a different goal each time you're on the algorithm, right?

00:36.008 --> 00:37.489
So you give it a goal to reach.

00:38.170 --> 00:41.293
Then the second thing here we see is planning.

00:41.793 --> 00:43.415
So it is a planning algorithm.

00:43.495 --> 00:44.476
What does planning mean?

00:44.516 --> 01:02.291
Planning means if you're traditionally reinforcement learning, you would think, ah, I'm just going to go ahead and run my agent here, and maybe you can move in the four different directions, run my agent here, do some things, right?

01:02.592 --> 01:05.374
Maybe I hit a wall, I get a negative reward, I try again.

01:05.354 --> 01:10.563
In planning, you don't have to move initially.

01:10.803 --> 01:15.852
What you can do is think about moving and you can think ahead of what's going to happen.

01:16.273 --> 01:19.839
And that's usually because you have some sort of model what happens.

01:20.279 --> 01:30.737
This is very famous applied in, for example, AlphaGo or AlphaZero, where you have, you know, if I move to the right here, I'm going to be here.

01:30.717 --> 01:34.586
So you will know once you've reached the goal, right?

01:34.666 --> 01:36.972
If I'm here, I go down, I reach the goal.

01:37.252 --> 01:37.473
Cool.

01:38.395 --> 01:42.024
So you can think all of this without actually moving in the environment.

01:42.044 --> 01:43.647
You can think yourself ahead.

01:44.048 --> 01:47.376
What would happen if I did certain things?

01:47.356 --> 01:53.005
And that in turn also means that you can think ahead multiple different paths.

01:53.326 --> 01:55.409
So you can think ahead, what would happen if I move right?

01:55.650 --> 01:56.852
What would happen if I move down?

01:57.633 --> 02:04.004
And then you can think in the next layer, if I move right, what would happen if I moved right again?

02:04.064 --> 02:07.069
What would happen if I moved down instead?

02:07.049 --> 02:12.235
So, you can easily see the planning problem becomes a tree search problem.

02:12.656 --> 02:16.641
In this case, we've done a breadth-first search.

02:17.021 --> 02:21.327
And eventually, you'll see that this will get you to the goal.

02:22.047 --> 02:27.454
So, this breadth-first search, or maybe you want to employ a depth-first search,

02:27.434 --> 02:29.737
will ultimately get you to the goal.

02:30.117 --> 02:32.119
We can represent this as a search tree.

02:32.239 --> 02:39.908
So you're here in a particular state and you have a bunch of actions, in this case four to move left, up, down, or right.

02:40.949 --> 02:45.494
And you can choose any of them and you will get into a new state.

02:45.514 --> 02:47.997
And from each of those, you could choose any again.

02:48.197 --> 02:52.202
And you can think ahead, all of this, you can construct this entire tree.

02:52.562 --> 02:57.087
And one of these branches will lead you to the goal.

02:57.067 --> 02:57.608
promise.

02:59.390 --> 03:00.191
What is the problem?

03:00.251 --> 03:11.304
The problem is, if the path to the goal here is, let's say D steps long, then this tree here is going to be D layers deep.

03:11.945 --> 03:18.373
And in our case, that means we'll have four to the D nodes in that tree before we even reach the goal.

03:19.394 --> 03:24.220
And that is just a long, long, or a big tree.

03:24.660 --> 03:26.803
And we can construct all of it.

03:26.783 --> 03:34.753
So algorithms have come along, for example, the A star algorithm, where you can incorporate something like a heuristic.

03:34.813 --> 03:41.061
And the heuristic would be, well, it's generally good if I'm close to the goal in L2 distance.

03:41.081 --> 03:50.052
So you would not build the entire tree here, but you would prefer nodes that will bring you towards this heuristic.

03:50.173 --> 03:54.478
So this node down here is closer to the green node in terms of L2 distance.

03:54.458 --> 03:57.522
And this note down here is even closer, but then you're kind of stuck.

03:57.923 --> 04:02.669
So A star will explore a bit, probably along this wall here.

04:04.111 --> 04:08.397
And once you're here, you have a clear path again, right?

04:08.458 --> 04:11.542
So you can simply take the actions that minimize this L2 distance.

04:11.562 --> 04:16.088
So this will already get you to a real good point.

04:16.689 --> 04:23.098
Monte Carlo Tree Search, as it was employed in AlphaGo or AlphaStar, has a similar

04:23.078 --> 04:53.085
Structure where it after a certain while it stops and it evaluates a heuristic to say what's the the value here and so on so it isn't for some problems an even better method of Constructing the search tree in a way where you don't get overblown by the number So the Monte Carlo search tree in this algorithm refers to the fact that we are generalizing Monte Carlo Tree search from the let's say the AlphaGo paper

04:53.065 --> 04:56.950
So, what's the idea here?

04:56.970 --> 04:58.432
So far, we've known everything.

04:59.053 --> 05:00.174
The idea is the following.

05:00.555 --> 05:16.715
If I had an oracle, if I am the master here and I can tell the agent, agent, look, I guarantee you that this state right here in the middle, you will pass that state.

05:16.755 --> 05:21.081
If you want to reach the goal, you will pass this.

05:21.179 --> 05:21.780
For sure.

05:21.820 --> 05:25.829
If I tell this to the agent, now what can the agent do?

05:25.869 --> 05:31.240
The agent could say, oh, okay, if I know that, I can simply, I don't have to search for a way to the goal.

05:31.280 --> 05:40.639
I'd much rather search for a way from my start point to that point where I know that I'm guaranteed to be at some place.

05:40.619 --> 05:46.734
And then I can search also from a way from there to the goal.

05:48.117 --> 05:54.132
So this now, remember our path was D steps long for the original problem.

05:54.473 --> 05:57.480
This is now let's say D half long.

05:57.460 --> 05:59.143
each of these paths.

05:59.163 --> 06:01.428
And that means we just construct two trees.

06:01.909 --> 06:04.874
Each one of them is going to be four to the D half.

06:05.496 --> 06:07.900
And the other one is also four to the D half.

06:07.920 --> 06:14.052
And if we add them, that is much smaller than the original four to the D tree that we build.

06:14.032 --> 06:23.304
So right there, we have subdivided our problem into two sub problems, and each of them are much easier than the original problem.

06:24.285 --> 06:27.229
This paper basically does this recursively.

06:27.569 --> 06:35.179
So it will subdivide the problem by proposing some middle state where you are going to be at some point for sure.

06:35.159 --> 06:37.484
and that for sure we're going to take a look at.

06:37.845 --> 06:50.194
And then for each of those problems, again, it will try to subdivide it into subproblems and therefore recursively solve the subproblems until they're small enough that they can be basically solved in one step.

06:52.158 --> 06:53.421
So that's the big idea here.

06:54.970 --> 06:57.415
And this is illustrated in this point right here.

06:57.635 --> 07:05.632
So you are in this S0, the start state, and you want to go to this S infinity, the goal state in your case.

07:06.233 --> 07:14.430
What this paper does is it proposes to split the problem here in the middle and then simply solve the two problems recursively.

07:14.410 --> 07:23.420
Now, what is a bit confusing right here is that it is the planning already is a tree search, right?

07:23.460 --> 07:28.907
So a plan is like a tree, but we are searching over plans.

07:28.947 --> 07:37.937
So we're searching for the best plan, which means that we are searching over trees and that search itself is a tree search.

07:37.917 --> 07:47.247
So the search itself is a problem where we go down one route and then, oh no, and then we maybe go down another route and here and then here.

07:47.587 --> 07:50.029
So the search is a tree.

07:50.370 --> 07:53.193
So we're now tree searching over trees.

07:53.753 --> 07:56.256
That's the kind of tricky thing to remember.

07:56.776 --> 08:04.645
So each of these plans, even if it's half, if it's only half done, like this is only half a plan, we don't know what's going to happen in here.

08:05.305 --> 08:07.047
This half a plan

08:07.027 --> 08:11.552
is a node in the tree that we're searching over.

08:12.293 --> 08:16.939
And then it splits as you can see here into two sub-problems.

08:17.299 --> 08:21.424
The two sub-problems also are nodes in that search tree.

08:21.524 --> 08:29.894
So you see that this top thing here would correspond to this node, even though in itself it is a plan, a tree, a string in this case.

08:30.515 --> 08:36.882
And each of the two sub-problems would become these nodes in the search tree.

08:36.862 --> 08:41.400
So keep that in mind as we go through this paper.

08:42.524 --> 08:46.500
It is very easy to get confused in this respect.

